  "def": "Imperative programming restricted to sequence, selection and iteration — no arbitrary goto.",
  "problem": "Tame the \"goto spaghetti\" of early code with disciplined, nestable control structures.",
  "mechanism": "Build all control flow from three composable constructs (sequence, if/switch, loops) plus subroutines; single-entry/single-exit blocks.",
  "benefits": [
    "Far more readable, analysable flow",
    "Enables reasoning & static analysis",
    "Foundation of every modern language"
  ],
  "limits": [
    "Early-exit dogma can hurt clarity",
    "Says nothing about data/state organisation"
  ],
  "failures": [
    "Deeply nested arrow code",
    "Boolean flags emulating goto"
  ],
  "whenNot": [
    "Rare low-level cases where a guarded jump is clearest (e.g. C error cleanup)"
  ],
  "myths": [
    "\"goto is always evil\" — disciplined jumps (error cleanup) are sometimes the clearest option"
  ],
